-- Japan, India, Taiwan, Thailand, Singapore: Asia Bond, Currency Preview
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-06-24T23:02:16Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-24/japan-india-taiwan-thailand-singapore-asia-bond-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: The statistics bureau is forecast to report at 8:30
a.m. that Japan’s consumer prices excluding fresh food fell 1.3
percent from a year earlier in May, according to the median
estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey of economists.
Japan’s Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku will hold media
briefings after a cabinet meeting.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
fell four basis points to 1.125 percent, according to Japan
Bond Trading Co., the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.
The yield was the lowest since August 2003.  
 The yen traded at 89.63 per dollar at 7:59 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 India: The central bank will sell 150 billion rupees ($3.2
billion) of bonds maturing in 2015, 2020, 2027 and 2032 today.
The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.60
percent. The rupee was at 46.495.  
 South Korea: The central bank will release the consumer
confidence survey for June today. The sentiment index rose in
May for the first time in seven months.  
 The yield on South Korea’s 4.50 percent bond due in March
2015 was 4.56 percent. The won was at 1,196.85.  
 Taiwan: The Council for Economic Planning and Development
will release the leading index for May on June 28. The measure,
a gauge of economic conditions three months ahead, climbed 0.4
percent in April from the previous month.  
 The yield on the 1.375 percent bond maturing March 2020
was 1.40 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The
Taiwan dollar traded at NT$32.216 per dollar.  
 Thailand: The central bank will sell 70 billion baht
($2.16 billion) of 14-day bills today. The yield on the 3.875
percent bond maturing in June 2019 was 3.18 percent. The baht
was at 32.42.  
 Singapore: Industrial output grew 37.2 percent in May from
a year earlier, compared with a 51 percent gain in April,
according to a Bloomberg News survey before the government
releases the data today.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent notes due September 2020 was
2.47 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3919.  
 Philippines: The National Statistics Office will publish
the trade data for April today. The trade deficit was $362
million in March.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.76 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 46.32 per dollar.  
